metadata.name: life is a (beautiful) mess #41
metadata.description:
when carefully applied, chaos brings things to life.

'life is a (beautiful) mess' was created as i led a certain amount of chaos take control of an animated textile algorithm i'm developing. 
as soon as it happened i realized that it was a great representation of our lives. 
each line represents one of us and the patterns that appear repeatedly are the situations we live which make us move, feel and be in a certain way. 
the image created is the sum of our paths in this life, as they only make sense when we look at them as one.

---

i hope you find it pleasant to watch this animation, how it develops and grows during aprox 1'30"
there are pieces drawn with the 4 typical school pen colors: black, green, blue and red. also a multicolor and a rare dark mode features.


press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the animation
doubleclick the mouse to resume the animation

generative art created by mehno using p5js

metadata.name: Burn Garden #25
metadata.description:
Burn Garden is a generative art work representing plants that grow as if they were fire. The plants burn different kinds of fruits that are a metaphor for NTF tokens that are created. The tokens become lighter, evolve, transfer and start floating in the sky as if they were pushed up by the hot air of the combustion
-	Hit ‘s’ to save a hi res (3072x3072) png file

metadata.name: Orbitants #1
metadata.description:
This is a generative system based on a random network of particles that follow each other. The rules are very simple, but a lot of variation emerges from the structure of the asymmetrical links between the particles.

It is a new implementation of a Processing sketch from year 2009. Captures of the original work can be seen here: https://flickr.com/photos/solaas/albums/72157623074296726

Controls:
[SPACE] to pause / play. 
[r] to reveal the underlying structure / return to path drawing
[s] to save image capture
Mouse press or touch to disturb the structure

This token has no features. Parameters are few and fixed. All the variation comes from the random network configuration and initial particle position.

metadata.name: partition() #71
metadata.description:
This token continuously partitions the canvas, sometimes taking minutes to create tens of thousands of subdivisions. Each token has unique properties that govern partition number and shape, and a random chance to freeze a partition. This allows for a wide variety of outputs, all driven by pure randomness.

Properties describe the entropy of the final output, the final number of partitions, and a rare small chance for filled partitions. This token also has a few interactive features as well (see below).

Software | p5.js
Created  | 11/30/21
Artist   | nicthib

Controls:
1-9: Displays the construction of the piece at each iteration
p: Save a png of the current canvas
s: Save an svg of the current canvas (Note: this can break the live sketch, so reload the page if you want to interact further)
Space: Resets animation
Scroll, click/drag: zoom/pan

metadata.name: Natural selection #59
metadata.description:
Of all the artworks I have made, this highly conceptual work is my favorite.

This NFT simulates natural selection in a limited population. 

Each individual in the population has their own DNA: a string of 41 letters. In the first generation of the simulation, each individual has completely random DNA.

For each new generation, the two 'fittest' individuals from the previous generation are allowed to reproduce, with their offspring carrying a combination of the DNA of both parents and some random mutations. 

The fitness of an individual is given by the number of letters of their DNA that match the sentence: "Natural selection is anything but random" (a quote from Richard Dawkins).

In total, 40 generations are simulated. The DNA of the fittest individual from each odd-numbered generation is printed.

The probability of a random piece of DNA equals the quote is one in 95^41 ≈ 10^80, roughly the number of atoms in the universe.

Source code: https://turtletoy.net/turtle/2f92cd6aa3
